"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by\n:\n Emergent Disease Foundation\n \n&#xa0;\n1.0 \nIntroduction to EDF&#xa0;\n1.1 \nThe \nEmergent Disease Foundation\n (EDF) is a UK-based public health education and research charity. The charity is both headed and supported by highly qualified academics, \npsychologists, \nbiologists, veterinarians and medical scientists with extensive backgrounds in public health, medicine\n, wildlife biology, species conservation, and animal welfare.\n EDF’s scientific base is necessarily derived from diverse disciplines because the charity’s main focus, zoonotic disease, involves a multi-\nfactorial cause\n history\n that emerges from human habits,\n poor animal welfare, ecological disturbance and general pathogenesis.\n \nDisease associated with exotic pet trading and keeping represents a key interest for EDF, and the primate pet trade is highly relevant to our work.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n2.0 \nExotic pet trading in general&#xa0;\n2.1 \nExotic pet trading and keeping historically attracted significant concern and criticism\n. However, i\nn recent years there has been a particularly \nexpansive\n raft of published \nevidence-based \nindependent scientific reports and articles\n establishing that exotic pet trading and keeping\n p\nresents serious problematic areas.\n \nThese problematic areas\n and sample publications,\n include:\n&#xa0;\n2.2\n \nanimal welfare\n \ninvolving both wild-caught and captive-bred sourcing, holding, transport,\n \nsale, and domestic\n maintenance (\nfor example, \nAkhtar, 2012; Altherr &amp; Freyer, 2001; Arena &amp; Warwick, 2004; Arena, Steedman &amp; Warwick, 2012; \nAuliya, 2003\n;\n ENDCAP 2012; GAO 2009; \nKoch et al, 2013;\n \nLaidlaw, 2005; McLennan 2012; Toland et al., 2012; Warwick, Lindley &amp; Steedman, \n2011a,b)\n \n&#xa0;\n2.3 \nspecies\n and \necological\n conservation\n involving\n depletion of natural populations, alteration of habitat, and introdu\nction of invasive alien species\n \n(for example, Andreone et al., 2008; Bomford 2008; Bomford et al., 2009; Faraone et al., 2008; \nFicetola et al., 2007; Fischer &amp; Garner, 2007; Fouquet &amp; Measey, 2006; Henderson &amp; Bomford, 2011; Kark et al., 2009; Keller et al., 2011; Kolbe, et al., 2004; Krauss et al., 2003; Langton, Atkins &amp; Herbert, 2011; Lillo et al., 2005; Rebelo et al., 2010; Rh\nyne et al., 2012; Scalera, 2007; Shine et al., 2009; Shine et al., 2010; Simon et al., 2011; Skerratt et al., 2007; Strayer et al., 2006; Vilà, et al., \n2010)\n \n&#xa0;\n2.4 \npublic health and safety\n \ninvolving the transmission of disease from non-human \nto human anima\nls, and injuries\n \n(for example, Abbott &amp; Janda, 2012; Aiken, Lane &amp; Adak, 2010; Arena, Steedman &amp; Warwick, 2012; Bertrand et al., 2008; Brow\nn, 2004; \nBrugere-\nPicoux &amp; Chomel, \n2009; Chomel et al., 2007; GAO, 2009\n; Hale et al., 2012; HPA, 2009; Jones et al., \n2008; Karesh et al., 2007; Mettee Zarecki et al\n.\n, 2013; Nenoff et al\n.\n, 2012; Praud &amp; Moutou, 2010; Smith et al., 2012; Smith &amp; Whitfield, 2012; TRAFFIC, 2012; \nW\narwick, Arena &amp; Steedman, 2012; \nWarwick et al., 2012; \nWarwick &amp; Corning, 2013; \nWarwick &amp; Steedma\nn, 2012\n).\n&#xa0;\n2.5 \nAllied concerns have also been raised about antibiotic resistance associated with\n \nboth (unsuccessful) industrial and general endeavours to control or eradicate microbial agents (for example, Aklilu et al., 2012; Rose et al., 2013; Smith et a\nl., 2012).\n&#xa0;\n3.0 \nPrimates&#xa0;\n3.1 \nEssentially, few subjects in bioscience have been either as frequently highlighted or as well furnished with evidential support as the growing concerns surrounding all types of exotic pet trading and keeping.\n \nPrimate pet trading and keeping epitomizes all problems associated \nwith \nexotic pets. \nFor EDF, control and pre\nvention of zoonotic disease is of\n primary concern\n, and primates, because of the close evolutionary, genetic, and habitual similarities to humans, m\nanifest a highly notable pathogenic risk to h\nu\nmans\n.\n \nPrimates harbour a substantial raft of potential human \npathogens, notably, but not exclusively, viruses. Viruses are the most difficult of pathogens to eradicate from an occupied reservoir \nand they are al\nso the most difficult to ‘treat’ in affected carrier or sick \nprimates and \npeople.\n Captivity-stress and general husbandry conditions for p\nrimates are, in our view, also\n major elevator\ns\n of risk in the domestic environment.\n&#xa0;\n3.2 \nPrimates, a\ns highly and vitall\ny social animals, require\n the interact\nions of relevant conspecifics. For people, t\nhis sociality is frequently a driver for acquiring primates, and keepers typically \nregard \nclose interaction between themselves and their ‘pets’ as essential. However, \nsuch \ncontact\n \ncreates a fundamentally negative situation in which ‘necessary’ human-primate interaction\ns increase\n the inherent risks of zoonoses transmission.\n&#xa0;\n3.3 \nResponsible management for primates is \noverly\n challenging. \nWe have tested a range of primate speci\nes found in\n the UK for their suitability or\n unsuitability as pets using \nboth \nthe \nSchuppli &amp; Fras\ner \n(2000) \nand \nthe EMODE \n(Warwick et al., 2013) \nmanagement assessment \nsystem\ns. \nAll primates scored \nin the \nexceptionally challenging and\n high in the ‘Difficult’ a\nnd ‘Extreme’ scale, so as to be regarded as beyond the abilities of the general public to care for them well \nor\n \nsafel\ny.\n&#xa0;\n4.0 \nConclusions&#xa0;\n4.1 \nWe are unable to determine the \nextent of trade in primates in the UK. However, we consider the nature of the \nproblems associated with primate trading and keeping to\n \nbe sufficiently concerning that, regardless of scale, the issues warrant \nvery serious concern.\n&#xa0;\n4.2 We regard the existing framework of ‘controls’\n on primate trading and keeping\n to be unacceptable and\n insufficiently modifiable to offer meaningful improvement.\n&#xa0;\n4.\n3\n \nThere can be little doubt that the scientific evidence collectively and overwhelmingly determines that primate trading and keeping is fundamentally harmful on all major fronts. \nIt is widely accepted that primates constitute a special zoonotic risk due to their evolutionarily close \nrelationship\n with humans. \nThere also can be little doubt that\n, both from anecdotal and scientific assessment \nu\nsing formalized evaluation tools,\n reasona\nble primate maintenance is beyond the \ncap\nabilities of the general public and many specialised husbanders alike.\n The consequences of these serious deficiencies involve highly negative\n, and in our view, unacce\nptable\n implications and results \nboth \nfor \npeople a\nnd \nfor \nprimates\n \nintended as pets\n.\n&#xa0;\n5.0 \nRecommendations&#xa0;\n5.1 \nGiven \nboth the historical and current concerns\n surrounding the primate pet trade\n, together with the ineffectiveness of \nremedial \neducation, it is our firm view that the only pragmatic, rational and\n ethical\n recommendation we can offer in order to control and prevent \npotential\n problems \nis to institute a total ban on\n all future trade and keeping of\n these animals.\n&#xa0;\n5.2 With regard to \nhow ban might be implemented\n, given the different problematic issues a\nssociated with primates as well as the different potential legislative options, we consider this a matter for the Committee to decide.\n&#xa0;\nWe trust this summary and recommendation is helpful to the Committee.\n&#xa0;\nJanuary 2014\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nReferences&#xa0;\nAbbott, S.L., Ni, F.C.Y. &amp;\n Janda, J.M. (2012). Increase in Extraintestinal Infections Caused by Salmonella enterica Subspecies II–IV. \nEmerging Infectious Diseases, \n18(4):637-639.\n&#xa0;\nAiken, A.M., Lane, C. &amp;\n Adak, G.K. (2010). Risk of Salmonella infection with exposure to reptiles in England, 2004-2007. \nEurosurveillance, \n15(22)